# Universal Rules — Reliability & Maintainability

> Extends [root AGENTS.md](../AGENTS.md). Cross-cutting — applies to all domains and tech stacks.

## Engineering Principles

These principles underpin every rule in this system. When a specific rule doesn't exist,
apply the relevant principle.

### Reliability
- Fail loudly, not silently. Empty catch blocks are forbidden.
- Handle unhappy paths explicitly before the happy path is "done".
- Require tests for new behavior and regressions.
- Prefer deterministic outcomes over clever abstractions.

### Maintainability
- Prefer small, cohesive modules (< 200 lines per service/component).
- Prefer small, reviewable incremental changes over large rewrites.
- Name things to communicate intent, not implementation.
- Prefer updating docs and examples in the same change as behavior changes.
- Prefer stable public interfaces that hide implementation details.
- Prefer composition over inheritance when both fit equally well.

### Testability
- Side effects sit at boundaries — pure logic in the middle.
- New business logic must have a clear unit test path.
- Each test file tests one unit of behavior, not a whole module.

### Operability
- Systems must be observable: logs, traces, metrics.
- Error messages must accelerate diagnosis, not obscure it.
- Prefer standard platform primitives over custom infrastructure behavior.

### Performance
- Optimize known bottlenecks, not hypothetical ones.
- Avoid hidden N+1 queries, `KEYS *`, and unnecessary iteration in hot paths.

## Always

- Handle every error explicitly — log, rethrow, or wrap. [MUST]
- Use `unknown` instead of `any` for external data. [MUST]
- Add a test file for every new source file. [MUST]
- Update or add automated tests when behavior changes. [MUST]
- Write tests around observable behavior and stable contracts, not private implementation details. [MUST]
- Update docs/examples when public APIs, workflows, or config contracts change. [MUST]
- Keep functions focused — one responsibility per function. [SHOULD]
- Keep files under 400 lines; extract when approaching 800. [SHOULD]

## Never

- Never swallow errors silently with empty catch blocks. [MUST]
- Never use bare `any` type in TypeScript. [MUST]
- Never commit code with failing tests. [MUST]
- Never optimize before profiling shows a real bottleneck. [MAY]

